5:
The two of us were originally
researchers from the Farlands, you
see.
8:
We were both driven by a common
passion.
12:
"Common passion," my arse. If I
remember correctly, YOU were the
one who apprenticed under ME.
17:
Heh. Thinking back on it, you just
might be right. I'd nearly forgotten.
20:
And how'd it all end, again? Oh
yes—the woman who was your
disciple eclipsed you... Then you ran
away with your tail between your
legs.
24:
Huh. Is that so? By my calculations
that'd mean you were in the
Farlands around fifty years ago.
33:
I mean, she IS the founder of the
academy.
By the by, what were you two
studying at that time, exactly?
37:
The fundamental principles of
magic. We were trying to uncover
the truths that lie hidden therein.
40:
The Farlands proved to be useless in
that regard—truly a country full of
narrow-minded imbeciles. They
didn't see the value in magic.
43:
They called light magic "divine" and
outlawed even the most simple
forms of dark magic—laughable,
really.
48:
That's as far as their feeble minds
could get them, no doubt. But the
truth of the matter is, there aren't
really six "elements"—there is only
the Void.
52:
The work of mages is, in essence, to
"discover" their own worlds within
the Void.
58:
My, this little pipsqueak's got it!
Exactly, my boy—the people with
awakened powers from that
newly-emerged city are proof of just
that.
62:
Riight. Suizen, could you give me a
quick "for dummies" breakdown on
all that mumbo-jumbo?
67:
Think about Nao, Yuki, and Shota...
They use their powers as if ignoring
the rules of magic entirely—as if
they're rewriting reality itself.
70:
That's because there aren't any
rules. Not truly. All that exists is
people—who nonetheless believe
that magic has rules, and that they
work.
75:
So it's almost as if they're all
dreaming? Just like back in Shibuya...
80:
I'm merely describing the scope and
effect of magic. No matter how
much people may wish for the
world's cruel ways to change, they
won't.
85:
Not quite. Human will can indeed
change the world. It has that
power—small though it may be.
88:
"The will is the brush which paints
the world," to quote a line from my
own research.
94:
You, on the other hand, wanted
nothing to do with mankind. That's
why you scurried off and built this
hole of yours, isn't it?
99: The Kaleidoscope. You built it, Gram?
104:
Yes. As a part of my search for the
dragons!
107:
Mankind's appearance on this world
was an abrupt one—almost as if
they were led here intentionally.
111:
But the dragons... They're different.
They've existed here since antiquity.
Back then, they were possessed of
even greater wisdom and power!
115:
The farther back in time one goes,
the fiercer their might! Their very
existence flies in the face of nature's
laws. Truly, they are the singularity!
119:
Someone really loves talking about
dragons, huh.
125:
It's not mankind that has the power
to give shape to the Void and create
worlds—it's the DRAGONS! That's why
I've been searching for it... The Origin
Dragon!
130:
...Weren't we talking about the
Kaleidoscope? How does this all
relate?
134:
The Dracostream! He excavated a
massive hole in the earth to gain
better access to it. That's why he
built the Kaleidoscope!
138:
Hahaha! But, just like with everything
he does, that bumbling fool failed!
His incantation went haywire and he
lost control of it.
145:
The spell was formulated PERFECTLY!
It should have worked!
156:
All the spell does is stimulate the
flow of mana to generate structural
configurations—dungeons, mazes,
and so on. There's no way it could
open a path to other worlds!
158:
But then... IT saw me. The Dragon's
Eye. By the time I realized it, the
Kaleidoscope had already become
something more than I ever
imagined.
165:
Looks like it wasn't your fault after all,
Alk. Someone had gone and
messed things up long before you
showed up.
169:
Yeah. I guess that makes Gram one
of our "partners in crime," doesn't it?
174:
Heh. I suppose it does. What a
concept.
178:
Nihilyana. Did you create the
academy to help Gram?
182:
As if! No, we'd already gone our
separate ways at that point. I had
no idea how spectacularly that
birdbrained dolt had screwed things
up.
185:
That being said, I've had my eye on
him these past years. I knew
something smelled fishy, and I WAS
planning on apprehending him...
188:
But it looks like I've run out of time.
We all have—the world is teetering
on the brink, it seems.
192:
The appearance of that town is
warping people's "view" of the world.
And as I said earlier, that is more
than enough to start changing its
very fabric.
196:
The "holes" in the Kaleidoscope
continue to expand... And what's
worse, that creature from the other
side grows stronger than ever...
201: "The other side?" What do you mean?
206:
An unwanted visitor from a realm
far, far away. You've no doubt heard
its whispers. Seen those who have
been touched by its many hands.
214:
Surely you remember the serpents!
THAT is the destiny of a dragon who
attempts to gain control over the
Origin Dragon's true power.
219:
So that's why serpents were always
trying to invade the Kaleidoscope...
224:
Gonna stop you there before you go
on another rant—it seems, at least,
that our interests are aligned.
227:
You want to make up for your past
blunder... As do we. I can see a world
where we help each other out.
231:
Singularities... Hmm. We could
simply plug those off-world drifters
into the Kaleidoscope's "holes" to act
as sacrifices—though it would be
little more than a stopgap.
240:
Especially if it won't even fully solve
the problem.
Still... You may be on the right track
with this "plugging the holes" idea.
245:
This boy's got his head on straight!
Still, you must realize this is far
easier said than done.
248:
Worlds are coming apart at the
seams. We'd need to sew them back
together—to dip one foot into
madness and somehow stay sane
doing it.
251:
Where can we find those brilliant
enough to accomplish that? Besides
myself, I mean.
260:
You... Tell me, boy. Do you have this
power? Are you of multiple worlds?
265:
I have knowledge of the
phenomenon, yes—though I don't
know if I would call myself "brilliant."
268:
How many others like me do you
have need of?
274:
Hah! Gram, would you look at this!
This boy's going to show us up! Not
that it's particularly hard to make
YOU look small.
279: They're a bunch of freaks, I tell you...
283:
Would you grant us some time to
make the necessary preparations?
